On August 25, 2017, President Donald J. Trump issued executive orders related to foreign policy. The orders were issued in response to recent actions and policies of the Government of Venezuela, including human rights abuses, a deepening humanitarian crisis, the establishment of an illegitimate Constituent Assembly, public corruption, and repression of the political opposition. The orders prohibit certain transactions, financing, and dealings related to the Government of Venezuela and its entities. They also prohibit the purchase of securities from the Government of Venezuela, with certain exceptions. The Secretary of the Treasury, in consultation with the Secretary of State, is authorized to take necessary actions to implement the orders. The orders take effect on August 25, 2017, at 12:01 a.m. Eastern Daylight Time.